        "text": "In 2014 civil funerals appeared for the first time in the Romanian legislation through inclusion in a new funeral law (1). This article will explore when and how civil funerals – by which we mean funerals where individuals consciously choose to exclude clerical assistance and a church service – appeared in 19th-century Romania. We will also analyse the impact of social, political and cultural changes in the first half of the 20th century on the organisation of the few secular funerary ceremonies we were able to trace in the printed press until 1939. This article breaks completely new ground, since the topic of non-religious, civil funerals is practically unknown in Romanian historiography, with the exception of one ideologically charged article from the 1960s on the first unsuccessful attempt to organise a civil funeral in 1879 (2).\n\nAs in other countries, 19th-century anticlericals and socialists began to use civil funerals to defy religious authorities. Studying the history of civil funerals will help us understand how anticlericals in Romania publicly tried to denounce religious beliefs, rituals and morals during the late 19th – and the first half of the 20th century, before a decades-long Communist rule took a hostile stance against religion under the influence of Marxist-Leninist atheism (3). We searched for mentions of civil funerals in the most important\n\nRevue belge de Philologie et d’Histoire / Belgisch Tijdschrift voor Filologie en Geschiedenis, 95, 2017, p. 937-962"
